Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of the turnover tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Foreword
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the courts of auditors have the power to audit all public finances.
The declaration requires the courts of auditors to have the power to examine the tax collection as much as possible.
The organisation of the European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VIth EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenue by the courts of auditors.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit work of a Court of Auditors is the development of a specific strategy for the audit of public revenue.
This is especially true for taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly intertwined and interdependent, a situation may arise in which national courts of auditors can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the courts of auditors of other states.
As an example, the investigation of internationally organized fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant revenue losses in many states.
Cooperation between the authorities is needed in the fight against such crimes.
Audit bodies in this area must be prepared to work closely with each other.
The idea for an audit of the VAT and the VIES system was developed at the VIth EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Office.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating courts of auditors first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
On the basis of the evaluation of the available information, we made the selection of the audit items for the audit planning.
Achieving the efficient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual states (in particular EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and create greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only contribute to improving the work of financial management, but also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of the turnover tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Introduction
File number: CZ) 06/27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215
Subject of examination:
 (CZ) Administration of VAT after the Czech Republic's accession to the European Union
 (DE) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of VAT pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004
The Commission's audit objective:
 (CZ) The aim of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the tax administration in the area of turnover tax after the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter "EC") with free movement of goods and services, as well as the use of VIES1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community supplies.
 (DE) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control with a focus on administrative assistance in the area of turnover tax in accordance with the regulations mentioned above.
As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations made to remedy them.
The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NKÚ") and the Federal Court of Auditors ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.
The cooperation focused on the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs from the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international administrative assistance between the financial administrations and the comparison of the VAT administration systems in the two states.
A joint final report on the results of the audits was prepared in accordance with European guideline no. 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI auditing standards.
The audit covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two courts of auditors.
In addition to the "exchange of information" priority under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation 1925/2004, other closely related issues have also been examined, such as the registration of taxable persons, tax returns and summary notifications.
In addition, the examination also covered the legal situation for cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach and the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two states, differences were found in the following areas:
1) Registration for VAT purposes.
While in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the essential criterion for registration is exceeding the turnover threshold laid down in the VAT Act.
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers only receive a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, the taxable person receives a tax number only applicable to domestic transactions for the purposes of sales tax.
If the German taxpayer wants to make intra-Community transactions, he must request the grant of a special identification number, the so-called USt-IdNr.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach.
In the Czech Republic, the international carriage of passengers by bus and coach is exempt from VAT, but there is a right to deduct VAT.
In Germany, the transport service, as far as the route passes through Germany, is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to unify the situation under Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of turnover taxes (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
Whereas in the Czech Republic, taxable persons are required to file VAT returns only for periods of less than one year (month or quarter), taxable persons in Germany (monthly or quarterly) 
VAT pre-registrations and a VAT annual declaration after the end of the calendar year.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, tax payers in Germany have to submit their VAT registrations electronically.
The introduction of the mandatory electronic filing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of Czech financial management (see 4.3).
4) Summary messages.
While taxpayers in the Czech Republic have to submit their summary notifications to the tax authorities (FÄ), German taxpayers have to submit the summary notifications to the CLO2.
Accordingly, the information from the summary notifications will be available to the FÄ in the Czech Republic immediately after their submission.
The information from the summary notifications will only be available to the German authorities after they have been processed by the CLO.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community transactions is needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summary notifications would shorten the period between the date of the turnover and the update of the VIES data.
This would allow for a timely assessment of taxation in the acquirer's Member State (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same time limits.
5) International exchange of information in the area of sales tax.
In the case of in-depth requests for information, the Czech CLO monitors compliance with the three-month period.
The German CLO does not monitor the processing times.
As a result, the German financial administration has completed a significantly lower percentage of requests for information within the prescribed period.
Because of these problems, the BRH has recommended to the German CLO a permanent monitoring of the deadlines (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is in the process of developing its own risk management system (RMS) with corresponding strengths and weaknesses.
The NKÚ and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of a RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5.).
As part of the cooperation, the two courts of auditors examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions carried out between Czech and German tax subjects.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed using CLO's legal options, where there were doubts about the correct taxation or the suspicion of VAT fraud.
The Courts of Auditors found that:
In some cases, the FÄ took advantage of the information obtained in the international exchange of information and re-established the VAT liability of the taxable persons concerned.
In these cases, the taxable persons either unlawfully claimed the VAT exemption or did not declare the purchase of goods in their VAT declaration.
In some cases, the FÄ could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal requirements in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial management of another Member State refused to provide the requested information.
A number of cases have been uncovered in which tax payers have inaccurately reported transactions in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in the VIES were accordingly incorrect, so that the clerks (the FÄ) had to investigate in these cases (see 6).
Examination procedure
Examination procedure in the Czech Republic
The audit was carried out between June 2006 and March 2007 by Department II - "State Budget Revenue" and the territorial audit departments of Central Bohemia, North West Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.
Audited positions were: Ministry of Finance and 10 FÄ Humpolec, Jihlava, Kadaň, Liberec, Nymburk, Otrokovice, Prague 1, Prague 4, Sokolov and Třinec.
The College of NKÚ approved the examination findings on 23 April 2007.
Examination procedures in Germany
The audit was carried out in the period July 2006 to February 2007 by the audit area of traffic taxes and employees of the associated PÄB Berlin, Frankfurt/Main and Munich.
It was part of the work plan for 2006 and was therefore announced to the Federal Ministry of Finance (BMF) in 2006.
After a test phase, the actual test began in the 4th quarter of 2006.
According to the cases selected by the BRH and later by the NKÚ, the BRH had to announce the examination in several federal states.
Apart from interviews in the BMF and the CLO, the examination was carried out in the following federal states:
Baden-Württemberg, Bavaria, Hamburg, Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, Rhineland-Palatinate and Saxony.
Tax records from the following cases were included in the audit:
Bruchsal, Ettlingen, Freudenstadt, Karlsruhe-Stadt, Leonberg, Mühlacker, Singen, Tuttlingen, Cham, Fürstenfeldbruck, München-Körperschaften, Munich II, IV and Munich V, Starnberg, Hamburg-Altona, Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg-Mitte, Hamburg-Nord and Hamburg for large companies, Hannover-Nord, Winsen-Luhe, Bonn-Innenstadt, Cologne-Mit Cologne-Porz, Cologne-South, Sankt Augustin, Pirmasens, Bautzen, Chemnitz-South, Dresden II, Freiberg, Leipzig I and Zschopau.
In addition, talks were held with the FÄ Augsburg-Stadt, Aurich, Düsseldorf-Altstadt, Eisleben, Kelheim and Verden.
The results of the examination were communicated to the BMF in May 2007.
Cooperation between the two courts of auditors
In the run-up to the parallel audit, several meetings were held between representatives of both courts of auditors.
Participants in these meetings familiarized themselves with the organization of financial management, the legislation on sales tax and the system of sales tax administration in the other country.
The subject of the test phase was agreed at the meeting in May 2006.
The results of the test phase were evaluated at the next joint meeting in August 2006.
At this meeting, a timetable for the further procedure was drawn up and the following examination topics were identified for the parallel examinations: 1.
Registration of taxable persons.
2.
International carriage of passengers by bus and coach - legislation in the Czech Republic and Germany.
3. International exchange of information, in particular the action of the tax officials in the processing of requests for information and the review of selected problem cases mentioned in the requests for information, as well as spontaneous information between the Czech Republic and Germany.
4. Tax returns.
5.
Summary notifications.
6.
Statistical information on deliveries and purchases between the Czech Republic and Germany.
7. Risk management in the VAT area.
At a meeting to coordinate the further examination of the NKÚ and the BRH in December 2006, both sides familiarised themselves with the examination procedure in the Czech Republic and Germany and discussed the results of the parallel examinations already achieved.
