An entrepreneur with a legal domicile, registered office or permanent establishment in the Czech Republic, whose turnover in the last 12 consecutive calendar months exceeds the amount of 1,000,000 CZK, will be liable for payment on the first day of the third month after the month in which he has exceeded the threshold (§ 94 (1) of Law No. 235/2004 Coll., concerning VAT; hereinafter "Law No. 235/2004").
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he has exceeded the registration threshold.
The current legislation does not allow the retroactive registration of a taxpayer who has exceeded the registration deadline.
A businessman with a legal seat, registered office or permanent establishment in the Czech Republic who provides services subject to VAT or services exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT must register for VAT even if his turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million, but he fulfils other conditions mentioned in Law No 235/2004.
An entrepreneur with a legal seat, registered office or permanent establishment in the Czech Republic, who does not meet any of the requirements laid down in the law, can voluntarily apply for registration for VAT.
The registration procedure pursuant to Law No. 337/1992 begins with the receipt of the application for registration by the local tax official.
If you want to register voluntarily for sales tax, you have to indicate in your application the date from which you apply for registration as a sales tax.
The financial officer has to check the information provided by the entrepreneur, i.e. the completed application for registration with all investments.
If he has doubts about the information given therein, he has to ask the applicant to explain, supplement or prove the information given.
If the financial officer has verified that the trader fulfils the conditions for registration, he has to give a written opinion on the registration and the allocation of a tax number.
In the communication, the tax official has to indicate the date of entry into force of the registration of the turnover tax and the assessment period for the sales tax.
The predisposition period is the calendar quarter, unless the entrepreneur's turnover for the previous calendar year has reached the amount of at least 10,000,000 CZK.
If this is the case, the predisposition period is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur whose turnover reached at least CZK 2,000,000 in the previous calendar year is entitled to choose the calendar month as a predisposition period and has to inform the tax officials of this change.
The issue of a tax number in the registration notice is always constitutive.
The taxable person must provide the tax number in every communication (including payments) with the tax official, and in cases where a special law requires it (e.g., Law No. 235/2004, concerning the preparation of tax documents) 3.
The tax number contains the coding "CZ" and a basic component in the form of a general identification mark.
In the case of natural persons, this is the number of the birth certificate or another general identification mark, to the extent specified by a special law. In the case of legal persons, the general identification mark is the company identification number (according to the provisions of Section 33 (12) of Law No. 337/1992).
If the entrepreneur has not fulfilled his obligation despite the appropriate request from the finance officer, the local finance officer has to register him ex officio.
A communication will also be issued to the taxpayer.
In the Czech Republic, every business-approved entrepreneur receives a tax number on his first registration for any type of tax.
This also applies to registration as a VAT payer.
Pursuant to Law No. 235/2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, in the event of non-compliance with the duty to register the turnover tax, the tax payer may demand that up to 10% of the proceeds of the taxable transaction, which the person concerned has unlawfully made without taxation, for the period from the date on which the trader should have been registered as a taxable person, until the date on which registration as a taxable person is made available by the tax officials took place (§ 98 (1) of Law No. 235/2004).
The payment of the fixed amount is considered a tax payment within the meaning of Section 98 (3) of Law No. 235/2004, i.e. it is not a fine or penalty.
If the legal requirements are met, the registration of a taxable person can be deleted for two reasons:
1) 
Cancellation of registration at the request of the taxpayer, i.e. mainly for the reason that the turnover does not reach the threshold for registration (§ 106 (1) of Law No. 235/2004).
A taxable person may request the deletion of his registration at the earliest one year after the date of entry into force specified in the registration notice.
2) Cancellation of registration ex officio (§ 106 (7) of Law No. 235/2004) if: a) the taxable person has not performed for 12 consecutive months and has not informed the tax officials of the reasons for this, b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under Law No. 235/2004, c) the former taxable person no longer fulfils the requirements for tax liability.
B) Taxable persons without a legal domicile, registered office or business premises in the Czech Republic A person who is registered for tax purposes in another Member State and does not have a legal domicile, registered office or permanent establishment in the Czech Republic or a taxable foreigner who provides services in the Czech Republic and who, in accordance with Section 108 of Law No. 235/2004, has to file a tax return and pay taxes for these services or deliveries ("non-resident entrepreneur ") the provision of the service in question is subject to tax.
He must apply for registration with the Prague 1 FA at the latest on the day of the delivery in question.
It is obliged to indicate in this application all VAT IDs allocated to it in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than on the day of the first taxable supply of services in the Czech Republic, the Prague 1 FA has to register him retroactively, since he became subject to VAT in accordance with Law No. 235/2004 on the day of the first taxable supply of services in the Czech Republic.
In the event of a retroactive registration, the Prague 1 FA must request proof (invoices or written explanations) of the performance from the operators concerned.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration in the Czech Republic before the first performance of a service, the Prague 1 FA has to request the submission of the performance-based contract documents.
As of December 31, 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with the Prague 1 FA, of which 124 were from Germany. As of December 31, 2005, a total of 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered, of which 233 were from Germany.
In accordance with the provisions of Section 106 (9) of Law No. 235/2004, the tax official is entitled to cancel the registration of a non-resident entrepreneur on 31 January of the following calendar year if he does not accept the obligation to file tax declarations or declarations and to pay taxes.
During the examination of the NKÚ, it turned out that in the case of filing a tax return by post with dispatch abroad on 25 January, i.e. according to the mandatory deadline for filing a tax return, this statement has not yet been received by the FA until 31 January.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant for the possibility of cancellation of the registration, become known to the FA later than 31 January, it is no longer possible to cancel the registration of the non-resident businessman for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year in question.
Registration of taxable persons in Germany
In accordance with the provisions of the tax regulations (§§ 137, 138 AO), every business must be registered with the municipality and/or the competent tax office.
This notification must be made no later than one month after the start of the business.
The municipality forwards the application to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office finds that a business activity has started but has not been registered, it can also register the taxable person ex officio retroactively.
In Germany, tax payers, regardless of whether they are resident or not, are obliged to register for Zwekke's sales tax if they meet the requirements of Section 2 of the German VAT Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the amount of sales generated.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
For foreign-based entrepreneurs, special funds are in charge.
For example, the FA ChemnitzSüd is responsible for those entrepreneurs who are based in the Czech Republic.
As of April 30, 2004, the total number of registered Czech entrepreneurs was 295; as of March 1, 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there.
According to the BRH, these bodies with special responsibilities often refused to register so-called bogus self-employed persons residing in the new Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since, after the accession of these ten countries to the European Community, the free movement of workers is still restricted, these self-employed people tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These employees do not fulfil the conditions laid down in § 2 UStG for recognition as entrepreneurs, as they are usually dependent on a single client who determines their working time and the type of work carried out.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must fill in a questionnaire from the competent FA and provide information on the company and the business activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a mandatory form for all FÄ in Germany.
It is processed either in special organisational units within the Agency or in the organisational units generally responsible for tax assessment.
With the help of this form, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual taxpayer prior to the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic transactions is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the responsible FA, The following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, The following five (or four) digits are the identification number for the taxpayer, the last digit is always a control digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he needs a VAT ID number in order to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries.
This is allocated by the CLO on request, if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for sales tax purposes.
The VAT ID number is automatically allocated by the CLO if the taxable person declares intra-Community supplies in his VAT registrations or in his annual VAT declaration.
The USt-IdNr. Is composed of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (e.g., if he stops doing business), but only after the completion of all tax transactions (the predisposition of all financial years) or 2. if the financial management determines that he no longer runs a business.
As a rule, the validity of the VAT ID number depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In these cases, the FÄ must inform the CLO of the deletion of the VAT number so that the validity of the VAT ID number can be terminated there at that time.
According to the value added tax law (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic taxpayers do not have to pay sales tax in the following cases: 1. the turnover of the previous calendar year plus the resulting sales tax has not exceeded the amount of 17,500 Euroand 2. is unlikely to exceed the amount of 50,000 Euroin the following year.
The so-called small entrepreneurs are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor are they entitled to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay sales tax, small business owners are required to register with the tax office and file an annual sales tax return.
A small business owner can explain the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the following five years.
He is then allowed to charge the sales tax and deduct the pre-tax.
Non-resident taxpayers can appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that they only make tax-free sales and refrain from deducting VAT.
The fiscal representative fulfils the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so that he does not have to register for VAT purposes.
The invoices indicate that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
While in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is the excess of the threshold amount specified in the VAT Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardised, but differences can occur due to different organisational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the taxable person receives a tax number for any tax at the time of his first registration.
In the case of its registration for VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for sales tax purposes receives a tax number exclusively for intra-German sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must specifically request the allocation of a VAT ID number.
Both NKÚ and BRH found that the German two-tier registration system could lead to significant misunderstandings in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which provides a single identification number for both national VAT registration and intra-Community transactions.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows for retroactive (national registration) in cases where the taxpayer does not register his business with the municipality or the competent FA.
This retroactive registration allows an accurate assessment of the value added tax for previous assessment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the value added tax liability.
As the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules should be harmonised for the whole EC.
The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Tax Office to every natural person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons resident in Germany for life.
If a natural person starts a business, the competent FA will apply for a commercial tax identification number that serves as a VAT ID number.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a taxable person and the allocation of the VAT ID number.
Work on the implementation of an IT procedure for the management of numbers has not yet been completed.
International carriage of passengers by bus and coach
The legal regulations in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of Section 70 of Law No. 235/2004, since 1 May 2004, the carriage of passengers between the individual Member States and between the Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and there is a right to deduct VAT.
The exemption from VAT applies even if the transport is carried out by persons registered as taxable persons in other Member States or by foreigners who are subject to tax in their own country.
The return journey is considered to be a separate transport operation.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than the cross-border carriage of passengers by bus and coach, they are not obliged to register in the Czech Republic as subject to VAT.
Cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic has been exempted from VAT in accordance with the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b).
"For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77/388/EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with point 17 in Annex F of the Directive, maintain the tax exemption for cross-border passenger transport either until the condition of Article 28 (4) of the Directive is met or until the same tax exemption is applied by any of the current Member States."
The legal regulations in Germany
According to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by Section 3b (1) of the UStG, a transport service is carried out where the transport is effected.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is subject to tax in Germany.
German taxation also does not distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident taxable person moves through Germany, the part of the transport that is attributable to Germany is considered to be a taxable transport.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must notify the competent FA of his intention to provide passenger transport services.
This registers it for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and gives a special certificate for each bus and coach named in the taxpayer's application.
The entrepreneur has to declare his taxable transport services in a German VAT declaration.
As of 1 March 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the Chemnitz-Süd FA.
If the transport service is provided to a domestic operator, the non-resident taxpayer does not have to pay the VAT himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic customer of the services has to pay the VAT to the tax office and the invoiced net amount to the non-resident taxpayer, which is referred to as "the transfer of the tax liability" and is in accordance with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident taxpayer and his income tax return, the German tax administration has several means of verifying the accuracy of the tax return in respect of taxable passenger transports:
Mobile customs control groups check the certificates of buses registered abroad, which are used for passenger transport through Germany.
After each inspection, the mobile control groups submit an inspection report to the responsible FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group can require the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident taxpayer can deduct the VAT paid in this way from the tax liability stated in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts about the accuracy of a VAT return, it can order an audit to be carried out in the FA, or it can use the means of mutual assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxable person refuses to pay the legally established turnover tax, the FA may request assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76/308/EEC.
The BRH considers these means of mutual assistance in tax matters for checking the VAT return or compliance with the tax obligation by a non-resident bus operator to be too burdensome in relation to the small amount of VAT on taxable passenger transports.
In particular, the examination of the books of a non-resident taxpayer incurs disproportionately high costs for the taxpayer himself and for financial management.
The latter must examine foreign books, which requires knowledge not only of the foreign language, but also of foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, the time required for such an examination is higher than for a resident taxable person, although the examination is limited to the passenger transports taking place in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must accept not only the audit rights of his national financial management, but also those of the other Member States, as far as he carries out passenger transports there.
In addition, for each Member State in which a single passenger transport is carried out, the taxable person must fulfil all existing tax obligations in the various languages and on the basis of the forms of the financial services of the EC Member States concerned.
This means that the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services will result in a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States, as well as between Member States and third countries, is exempt from VAT under the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic to the EC.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to a turnover tax in accordance with the transport route, which is part of the German territory.
If a non-resident taxpayer provides such a transport service for the first time, he must notify the relevant FA in advance.
This registers the taxable person, who must declare the taxable share of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
The law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech taxpayers registered with the Chemnitz-Süd FA have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The tax revenue in question is quite low in relation to the administrative burden.
Member States - which collect VAT under Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of value added tax - have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionate cost of VAT, cross-border passenger transport should only be subject to tax in one Member State.
This could be the state where the transport begins or where the service provider is located.
Such a form of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006.
VAT returns
Filing and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Unless otherwise specified by the law, even if no tax liability has been incurred, the entrepreneur is obliged to file a VAT return on the form specified by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the end of the tax period.
The tax liability arises at the end of the period for the filing of the VAT return. Except for this regulation, according to law No. 235/2004, the value added tax is on the import of goods. Here, the due date of the tax is determined according to the customs regulations.
If, as a result, an above-average amount of deductible tax is claimed for a refund, this amount will be refunded to the taxpayer within 30 days of the determination of the deductible, without having to make an application for it.
The time limit is not applied in cases where the tax officer initiates a tax procedure with regard to the taxable person's tax liability.
Pursuant to Section 73 (11) of Law No. 235/2004, the right to deduct VAT can be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the right to deduct VAT has arisen.
At the end of this period, the deduction can still be claimed within three years of the end of the tax period during which the claim would have been possible for the first time.
In order to do this, however, a supplementary declaration of VAT is required.
An amendment to Law No. 235/2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, allows the filing of a supplementary VAT declaration only for the period during which the right to deduct VAT could have been asserted for the first time.
A taxable person must file a supplementary VAT return if: (a) the sum of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax liability, (b) he makes corrections which do not alter the last known tax liability, but only change previous information, (c) he makes corrections to the VAT rate and the tax liability in accordance with Section 49 of Law No 235/2004.
A taxable person may file a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
