Filing and processing of VAT returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly VAT pre-registrations and the annual VAT return.
Those taxpayers who are required to file VAT pre-notifications will still have to file an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners, who are not obliged to pay the sales tax, have to make an annual sales tax declaration.
The taxable persons are, in principle, obliged to file a preliminary VAT registration by the 10th day after the end of the calendar quarter in which the turnover tax is generated (§ 18 (2) of the German Stock Corporation Act).
However, if the VAT liability is more than Euro6,136 in the previous year or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is obliged to file monthly VAT pre-notifications no later than the 10th day after the end of the month in question.
The taxable person can also opt for the filing of monthly VAT pre-registrations if he has received a refund of Euro6,136 in the previous year (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual turnover tax is not more than Euro512, neither VAT pre-registrations nor VAT returns are to be made.
A resulting VAT liability is to be paid 10 days after the end of the tax period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the financial management.
 (legal) deadlines for the processing of VAT returns and for the refund of VAT overpayments do not exist.
In order to receive a timely refund, a security for the refund amount can be offered.
In principle, VAT returns, including reimbursement cases, must be processed expeditiously.
The German VAT Act allows an extension of these (delivery or payment) costs (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the VAT pre-registration and the corresponding payments may be made one month later. However, in the case of monthly notifications, a special advance payment must be made for this.
This payment will be offset against the VAT liability established for the pre-notification period of December.
If an error is detected, the trader must file a corrected VAT pre-registration.
There is no "additional" VAT return.
Once the VAT return, which must be submitted by 31 May of the following year, has been submitted to the tax office, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect VAT pre-notification, but only the incorrect annual VAT return.
Corrections of this VAT return to the taxpayer's advantage or disadvantage are possible within four years after the end of the year in which the first VAT return was issued.
After the end of this four-year period, a VAT return can usually only be corrected in cases of a frivolous tax cut or tax evasion.
Taxable persons are required to file VAT pre-notifications by electronic means.
The FÄ can grant exceptions to this rule in order to avoid undue hardship.
The annual VAT return can be issued either in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the tax is not certified, the taxpayer must also make the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
If no VAT pre-notifications or declarations are made, the financial management is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover achieved by the taxpayer6.
In the event of a late levy, the taxable person may be subject to a late payment (up to 10% of the tax bill or up to an amount of Euro25,000).
In a previous audit, the BRH found that the FÄ often do not charge this delay surcharge.
In cases where the FÄ collected the delay surcharges, the amount was determined inconsistently and arbitrarily.
The delay surcharge therefore misses its purpose of reducing the average delay, in particular in the filing of the annual VAT return.
The form of the VAT return contains separate lines for value information on intra-Community deliveries or purchases.
There are also separate lines for the provision of services.
Non-taxable sales must be stated in a separate line of the VAT declaration.
The VAT returns filed on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially designated personnel.
The data of electronically filed tax returns are directly available to the financial administration.
