The introduction of the duty of electronic filing of the tax return in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of Czech financial management.
Summary notifications
Filing and processing of summary notifications in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of Section 102 of Law No 235/2004, a trader who supplies goods to a person registered in another Member State for tax purposes has to make corresponding summary notifications (hereinafter referred to as "ZM").
The value of the goods delivered is always stated in Czech currency in the Central Bank, broken down according to the VAT IdNr7, the individual taxable persons under which they are registered in the other Member State.
Information on services is not provided in the ZM.
The taxable persons with a calendar monthly or quarterly period of taxation have to hand over the ZM to the local FA no later than the 25th day after the end of each quarter.
Incorrect data must be corrected in a correction ZM within 15 days of the detection of the error.
Incorrect data in the ZM are always replaced by the data from the correction ZM.
Similar to the tax returns, tax payers can also hand over the ZM electronically.
If a taxable person does not issue a ZM or correction ZM, even though he is obliged to do so under Law No. 235/2004, the tax official shall ask him to surrender the ZM in question, pointing out the consequences of the non-delivery. In the event of non-monetary duties, the tax official shall be entitled to impose repeated fines of up to CZK 2 million in accordance with Section 37 of Law No. 337/1992.
The NKÚ found during its investigation that the FÄ mostly did not use its power to impose fines on its delinquent taxpayers.
In particular, in the case of the surrender of the ZM, the taxable persons are not sufficiently motivated to fulfil their duties, since the failure to surrender a ZM does not affect the amount of their VAT liability.
Pursuant to Section 102 (5) of Law No. 235/2004, the tax officer is obliged to check the information in the ZM or Amending ZM, to remove all ambiguities and to use the information to determine the tax liability.
