When purchasing goods from another Member State, the taxable person must state this in his VAT return and enter the value of the purchase in the lines of the VAT return specified for it.
Selected cases of differences between the value of the purchases made by the Czech taxpayer in his VAT return and the value of the goods supplied by the supplier from the other Member State in his VAT return will be forwarded by the CLO to the competent FA for examination.
The clerks there must investigate the deviations.
There can then be three different situations:
A) The value indicated by the Czech buyer in the relevant sections of his VAT return is lower than the value of the deliveries indicated by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, the financial officer checks the accuracy of the information.
B) The difference is zero.
This situation can be caused either by a change in the information within the EC (the foreign supplier corrects his ZM) or by a change in the information in the VAT return (the Czech taxpayer in the meantime gives an additional VAT return on his own initiative).
In this case, it is at the discretion of the tax official to check the accuracy of the information in the VAT return anyway.
C) The value of goods purchased from other Member States, as indicated by the Czech taxpayer in his VAT return, is higher than the value of the goods supplied by the suppliers of the other EC Member States.
Here, in turn, it is up to the Treasury official to check the accuracy of the information.
After reviewing the differences and clarifying the reasons for their occurrence, the Treasury official gives the results of his review in ATIS.
These results will be forwarded to the CLO.
