Filing and processing of the summary notifications in Germany
Traders who make intra-Community deliveries from Germany to other EC Member States or take part in triangular transactions are required to make quarterly ZMs listing intra-Community deliveries to purchasers (§ 18a (1) UStG).
The ZM must be surrendered no later than the 10th day of the month following the calendar quarter in question.
If a long-term extension is granted for the filing of VAT pre-notifications, this also applies to the ZM.
The ZM must be handed over to the CLO.
The electronic levy has been mandatory since 1 January 2007.
The competent FA may allow exemptions for individual taxpayers in order to avoid undue hardship.
If the taxpayer finds that the ZM was faulty, he is obliged to issue a correction ZM within one month.
In the case of non-delivery of the ZM, the CLO initiates an enforcement procedure.
This includes the following steps: - first reminder - second reminder, with the threat of a penalty payment and - setting the penalty payment.
Although the German tax code allows the imposition of a penalty payment of up to 25,000 Euro (§ 329 AO), the CLO imposes three penalty payments of 125, 250 and 500 Euro.
In addition, § 26a (1) No. 5 UStG states that the taxable person acts in a disorderly manner if, intentionally or frivolously, he does not give a ZM properly, completely or in a timely manner or if he does not correct a ZM or does not correct it in a timely manner.
This breach can be punishable by a fine of up to Euro5,000.
Data on intra-Community deliveries cannot be entered by the FÄ into the VIES, because only the CLO is responsible for the processing of the ZM.
The data of the ZM is only stored at the CLO.
The information from the summary reports is only available to the FÄ after their processing by the CLO.
The deadlines for processing ZM are laid down in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.
The data of the ZM must be stored within three months of the calendar quarter in question (in VIES).
In the case of incorrect VAT ID number in the ZM of German taxpayers, the German CLO receives a notification "O_MCTL" from the other Member State.
The CLO then turns to the entrepreneur and asks for the right data.
If the CLO fails to obtain the correct information, the case will be submitted to the relevant FA.
It is then up to them to request the correct information.
