In the Czech Republic, taxable persons who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered for VAT in another Member State must surrender a ZM to the local FA within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
The FÄ process the ZM and forward the data to the CLO.
The values of intra-Community supplies reported by the taxable persons in the Central Tax Office will be compared with the values of intra-Community supplies indicated by the same taxable persons in their VAT returns.
The results of the settlement will be taken into account in the tax assessment.
In Germany, taxable persons who have made intra-Community deliveries are obliged to pay quarterly VAT within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter10.
Since 1 January 2007, taxable persons have had to submit the ZM electronically to the CLO.
The data from the ZM are only available to the FÄ after their processing at the CLO.
In both the Czech Republic and Germany, the taxable persons in the ZM only declare the deliveries of goods.
The provision of services is not specified in the ZM. Unlike the Czech FÄ, the German FÄ cannot correct erroneous information in individual lines of the submitted ZM itself.
Due to this limited access to the German MIAS data, incorrect VAT ID numbers were not corrected even if the taxable person reported the correct VAT ID number to the FA.
