Differences between the data of the pre-notification and the ZM are regularly not revealed before the German CLO forwards the VIES data to other Member States.
On the basis of these findings by the BRH, it is obvious that a comparison would improve the reliability of the transmitted VIES data.
The data provided by other Member States on the supply of goods to Czech taxpayers will be compared in the Czech Republic with the data on purchases of goods indicated by Czech taxpayers in their VAT returns.
The Czech CLO makes the comparison for each calendar quarter separately.
The most serious cases of deviations are sent to the FÄ for examination.
Unlike the Czech tax administration, the German tax administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions.
Such general control will only be carried out on taxable persons who are not fully entitled to deduct VAT.
In addition, the German tax administration only controls the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions of other taxable persons if the RMS produces an audit report or if the taxable person has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves the FÄ from clarifying the reasons for any differences.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
In order to combat carousel fraud, updated information on intra-Community acquisitions must be available as early as possible.
The current system of the ZM, in particular VIES, provides financial authorities with information that may well be half a year old.
This time delay could be reduced to up to four months if taxpayers had to surrender monthly ZMs.
