The international exchange of information without prior request is either automatic, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
The tax officials of other Member States are often provided with information without prior request, which is important for determining the value added tax liability.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected at the CLO.
The exchange of information between the individual Member States takes place electronically.
"Automatic exchange" under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 means the systematic transmission of previously defined information to other Member States at regular, pre-determined intervals, without prior request.
"structured automatic exchange" means the systematic transmission of previously defined information to another Member State, without its prior request, as soon as the relevant information is available.
The Czech Republic informs the other Member States of the automatic exchange of information on deliveries of new vehicles.
The financial officer obtains this information from the pre-printed notification of the delivery of a new vehicle pursuant to Section 19 of Law No. 235/2004, as well as from the copy of the invoice issued.
When processing this form, the financial officer enters the required data into the corresponding document template and forwards it directly to the responsible employee of the financial directorate, where the data is collected and sent to the CLO for further processing, after which the data will be transmitted to the other Member States within the specified period, at the latest within two months of the end of the quarter in which they were obtained.
The Czech Republic also provides other Member States with information on mail order transactions that are tax-free in the country of origin, on intra-Community transactions that appear to be inadmissible and on potential "missing traders."
This information is transmitted to the other Member States by means of a SCAC form of spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information originates from the local FA.
The FÄ send the completed form SCAC 2004 by e-mail directly to the German CLO, which forwards the SCAC forms to the foreign CLO.
The FÄ are instructed to write their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the SCAC form used is one-size-fits-all.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the BRH were sent in order to ensure the taxation of employment in the other Member State or to prove the tax exemption of intra-Community supplies from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German CLO receives a request for information from another Member State, it checks whether the value of the deliveries specified in the request exceeds the minimum amount of Euro15,000.
If there is no reasonable justification for the request, the German CLO refuses to provide information regarding a turnover below the minimum amount limit.
In addition, the German CLO is concerned with the translation of freely formulated texts in the SCAC form [ (B1-17) or (E) ], if they are not written in German or English.
In order to answer the request for information, the CLO directs it to the responsible FA and refers to the three-month period.
No further deadlines have been set at the various levels of German financial management.
Although the German CLO has the technical means to monitor compliance with the deadline, it does not have the necessary personnel capacity to remind the FÄ of answering the unfinished requests for information.
The FÄ will receive the required information by writing to the taxpayer or conducting an external audit.
The external auditors usually choose between two types of audit: the special sales tax audit, which covers all taxable transactions within a period of several months, or the so-called sales tax review, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
This short and flexible form of examination does not require an announcement to the taxpayer and has proved its worth in the examination of a single turnover.
In the case of the automatic exchange of information, Germany provides the other Member State with the following information: - via USt-IdNr., which has been allocated to companies established in other EC Member States - on the refund of VAT to entrepreneurs established in other EC Member States.
In addition, Germany has undertaken to provide the following information to the other EC Member States in the framework of the structured automatic exchange of information:
A. The supply of new vehicles to traders without UStIdNr., b. distance selling (shipping) to other EC Member States not subject to VAT in Germany, c. Significant discrepancies between the purchases reported by a taxable person and the MIAS data transmitted by other Member States, i.e. intra-Community supplies of goods subject to taxation by the taxable person in Germany, e. potential "Missing Traders" which have made intra-Community transactions, regardless of whether their VAT number is still valid or has already been deleted, as well as for taxable persons who have made intra-Community deliveries to potential "missing traders" or to customers who have misused a VAT ID number.
Comparison and evaluation
The sending of requests for information or spontaneous information takes place both in the Czech Republic and in Germany on the initiative of the local authorities, who send the corresponding SCAC forms to the CLO.
While the Czech CLO uses bilingual SCAC forms (Czech-English) and translates information provided into English or German, the German FÄ follow the instruction to write requests for information or spontaneous information in a monolingual form only in German.
The German CLO does not produce translations of German texts.
When examining requests for information between the Czech Republic and Germany in the period 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005, the NKÚ found that the Czech financial administration handled 74.5% of the requests for information received within the three-month period, while the requests for information sent to Germany were only dealt with by the German financial administration in 40.6% of the cases within that period.
Although the German CLO refers the FÄ to the three-month period, it does not monitor its compliance.
Due to the absence of memories, there is a high proportion of time-limited requests for information.
That is why the BRH has recommended a continuous reminder procedure to the German CLO.
The situation has now changed.
According to the information available to us, the German CLO is now reminding the tax authorities to respond to the outstanding requests for information.
VAT risk management
Risk management in the Czech Republic
In the Czech Republic, several organizational units at different levels of financial management are involved in risk management in the area of sales tax.
Within the Czech Ministry of Finance, the following organizational units are responsible for risk management and the fight against VAT fraud:
The department of methodology and economic management of sales tax, or its risk management unit, deals with the identification of potential risk areas for tax revenue and evaluates the trends in these risks in domestic and intra-Community trade.
At the national level, this body coordinates the requirements for the "credibility of VAT returns" criterion and uses the VIES data to detect possible tax evasions in the context of intra-Community deliveries and purchases.
Based on data on the Czech Republic's trade balance, it evaluates risk-prone goods, prepares conceptual risk management in the area of sales tax and cooperates in this area with the relevant EC institutions and the other Member States.
The Department for International Administrative Assistance in the field of VAT provides inter alia for the exchange of information, participates in the creation and maintenance of a relevant information database, evaluates the data of other Member States available in the VIES system, carries out public relations work and is responsible for other forms of intergovernmental assistance within the meaning of Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003.
