The Tax Examination and Tax Investigation Department conducts, among other things, risk analyses in the context of the methodical control of tax audits, sets priorities for the work planning of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of cases to be examined, prepares risk analyses to combat tax evasion and, in this context, collects information from financial management and other sources and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax investigation bodies exist in the financial directorates. Their tasks include the search for taxpayers and sectors that are risky in terms of the frequency of tax evasion (e.g., Internet transactions, gold, pharmaceutical industry), the search for unregistered taxpayers (e.g., in the sectors of Internet services, employment services, electronic and print media, etc.), the investigation of links in chain fraud cases and the information of the local financial authorities.
Special testing units have been set up in 12 selected cases.
They have a regional competence and, on the basis of appropriate authorisation, carry out tax audits outside the local area of competence of the FÄ.
The need to set up the special audit units arose from the increase in identified new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, especially in the context of chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of the tax investigators or concentrate on taxable persons with certain activities, multinational companies and taxable persons with particularly high turnovers.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks in the area of VAT have been integrated into the ATIS system: - the task of "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk of tax returns, - the task of "selecting the taxable persons to be audited," selecting the taxable persons to be audited on the basis of certain criteria - the task of "MIAS" which allows tax officials access to the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The task of "MIAS" allows, among other things: - verification of the validity of the VAT ID of taxable persons from other Member States, - confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech taxable person, as indicated in the ZM by all suppliers of the taxable person from other Member States, - creation of a list of taxable persons who have not surrendered a ZM, - formal control of the information provided by taxable persons in the Czech Republic in their ZM. before this information is sent to other Member States - drawing up a list of taxable persons in whose VAT returns the information on goods delivered to other Member States does not match the information in the CMD - drawing up a list of taxable persons in whose VAT returns the information on the value of goods purchased from other Member States does not match the information in the CMD of all their suppliers from other Member States13.
As part of their mission to combat tax evasion, tax officials have access to data from public authorities such as commercial registers, land registers, motor vehicle registers, business registers, etc.
More detailed information can be found in Section 4.4.1 Dispensing and processing of summary notifications in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
Due to their federal structure, both the federal financial authorities (in particular the CLO) and the financial authorities of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and implementation of a RMS in the Federal Republic of Germany.
It is true that there are joint working groups for development, but neither the CLO nor the financial authorities of the federal states have a complete uniform database.
At the level of the CLO, the unit ST I 2 (hereafter "KUSS" - Coordinating Unit for special sales tax audits and tax investigation measures) collects the audit findings on fraud in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER has been set up at KUSS, where the tax authorities can enter and query the names of discovered Missing Traders or VAT fraudsters.
The KUSS coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experiences of the KUSS are brought into the development of the RMS through their cooperation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organizational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of UStIdNr. Of other Member States, which appear in the ZM of German taxpayers, will be carried out at the CLO.
This formal review takes place before the transmission of the ZM to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the VIES data and thus its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The validity check in the USt-IdNr., referred to in the ZM, is carried out on the basis of the O_MCTL identifiers sent by the other Member States (for the procedure for the correction of invalid USt-IdNr., see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the CLO's RMS is based on the VIES data transmitted by the other Member States and generates various types of notifications for the discovery of suspected Missing Traders, using certain characteristics that usually occur in carousel transactions.
The FÄ of the federal states are instructed to process these communications and have to forward the results of their investigations to the CLO in certain cases.
The audit by the BRH has confirmed that all available features must be included in order to conclude with sufficient probability a case of tax fraud (instead of focusing mainly on the turnover of a company).
Accordingly, the BRH has recommended to the BMF to work with combinations of different clues in the preparation of communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other factors, such as the payment behaviour of the taxpayer, the industry or the company's shareholdings.
A second level of risk management exists in the financial administrations of the federal states and focuses on the processing of VAT pre-registrations and annual declarations.
For example, the system draws up a list of those taxable persons who have indicated intra-Community supplies in their VAT pre-notification or annual declaration.
This list is sent to the CLO for the purpose of monitoring the complete surrender of the ZM.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the purchases indicated by the taxable person in his annual VAT return are compared with the data in the VIES.
The financial authorities of the federal states avoid a comparison of the quarterly data, as this would result in too many discrepancies, which are due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; e.g.:
- Suppliers and purchasers assume different timings for the execution of intra-Community sales;
- Different accounting records and tax declarations of Skonti and rebates.
In addition to comparing the information from the VAT returns with the VIES data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms, which are based on information in the VAT returns and certain other indications (e.g., company name, age of the owner/participant, number of employees and mode of payment of the taxpayer).
Bavaria has introduced a rules-based risk management system that allows a team of specialists in the fight against tax fraud (hereinafter referred to as "risk managers") to program their own rules in such a way that suspected tax fraudsters are filtered out.
This system is used in the processing of VAT pre-registrations by the FÄ.
This will give the responsible FA the advice of the RMS before the sales tax is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, the risk managers have to adapt the rules according to the feedback from the fae.
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of detected evasion cases.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system draws up a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent authorities decide on the examination of the taxable persons concerned.
After the audit, the tax auditors must report their findings so that the RMS can learn from the results of the audits it has proposed.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rules-based fuzzy system.
Based on a lot of data from processed VAT returns and some other evidence, this Neuro-Fuzzy system (also known as the data-mining system) calculates how likely it is that a taxpayer is entangled in tax fraud.
It then compiles a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, the FÄ selects the taxable persons concerned for examination and reports the audit results to the data centre in question.
The introduction of these three RMSs is underway in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems appears fit for purpose.
It remains to be seen whether the hoped-for effects will materialise in actual use.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in this report to deal with the specific criteria of the RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three German federal states mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud - in particular carousel fraud - has proved to be not a national problem, but an European one.
The people involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one, but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for a RMS need to be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State. If this is not the case, fraudsters will seek out the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is located.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud may be affected.
That is why there should be an European exchange of experience on the RMS.
Selected results from the examination of individual sales As part of the parallel examinations, the NKÚ and the BRH examined the quality and usability of information on selected deliveries or services.
Which were the subject of the international exchange of information between the financial authorities of the Czech Republic and Germany.
In addition, the two courts jointly examined the handling of several deliveries, which were in doubt about their implementation, or which the taxpayers of both states stated differently in the tax returns or ZM.
At the request of the BRH, NKÚ examined a total of eight business transactions between eight Czech and eight German taxpayers.
In addition, in 43 cases, on the basis of communications from the BRH, NKÚ examined the values of intra-Community transactions with Germany indicated by Czech taxpayers in their tax returns and ZM.
At the request of the NKÚ, the BRH reviewed a total of 23 deliveries between 23 German and 21 Czech taxpayers.
The relevant information was exchanged exclusively on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 on CLO.
The examination of the selected cases showed, among other things, that the different procedures for registration in the EC Member States lead to the problems mentioned in Chapter 4.1:
1.
According to the VIES data, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth Euro60,500 from a German taxpayer in the third quarter of 2004.
When the Czech taxpayer declared an acquisition of only Euro29,869, the Czech tax administration sent a request for information to Germany for the purpose of verifying the value of the goods delivered.
The German side stated in its reply to the Czech request for information that the German taxpayer in question had delivered goods worth Euro27,381 to his Czech business partner in the second quarter of 2004, Euro31,997 in the third quarter and Euro10,276 in the fourth quarter.
It also emerged from the reply that the VAT ID of the German taxpayer was not valid until 28 September 2004. However, the German CLO had accepted another application from the German taxpayer and brought forward the validity of the VAT ID number retroactively to 1 May 2004.
The German taxpayer corrected the ZM.
On the basis of this information, it was a (inter-Community) acquisition of goods by the Czech taxpayer.
Through a request to the competent tax office in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that in 2004 the Czech taxpayer had issued additional VAT returns for the individual (under-year) tax periods in which he declared a higher value of purchases from other Member States and at the same time sought the deduction of pre-tax from purchases from other Member States.
On the basis of these additional VAT returns, the competent clerk of the Czech tax office could not clearly determine whether the declared purchases also included the value of the deliveries of the above-mentioned German supplier.
In response to a request for information from the NKÚ, the BRH found that the German supplier had been registered as subject to VAT in September 2003.
Je-doch had not applied for the allocation of an USt-IdNr., but only a tax number applicable to Germany at the time of registration.
Although it is generally not possible in Germany to retroactively assign a VAT ID number to a taxable person, in 2006 the competent clerk of the German financial administration did so retroactively as of 1 May 2004.
The German CLO retroactively allocates an USt-IdNr. If the German entrepreneur did not cause the delayed allocation; e.g., if the CLO caused the delay after the taxpayer's request for the grant of an USt-IdNr.
In this case, the CLO grants the USt-IdNr. Retroactively, because the entrepreneur does not need a valid USt-IdNr. For an intra-Community delivery according to § 6 UStG.
Conversely, a German acquirer does not need the (valid) VAT ID of its supplier to declare the intra-Community acquisition.
Because of these procedural differences between the Member States, the German CLO granted USt-IdNr. Retroactively in this particular case.
2.
As part of the international exchange of information, the Czech tax official asked for a review of the German businessman's registration tax.
According to the VIES data, the date of registration is 5 March 2005, while a registration certificate issued by the local German FA indicates 1 October 2004.
In their reply, the German authorities announced that the German taxpayer had been registered on 1 October 2004, but had not been allocated a VAT ID number in Germany until 16 February 2005 for organisational reasons.
By request from the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ learned that the tax official had carried out a VAT check on the Czech taxable person for the tax periods from the third quarter of 2004 to the second quarter of 2005.
During this examination, the tax office found that the Czech taxpayer had declared in his VAT return services worth CZK 9,897 that he had provided to the German taxpayer prior to his registration (i.e. Before 1 October 2004).
The (Czech) tax office imposed a tax liability of CZK 1,880 on the Czech taxpayer for the third quarter of 2004.
On the basis of the NKÚ's request, the BRH found that the German taxpayer had not been allocated the VAT ID number until he registered his company, which was founded in 2004, with the FA on 16 February 2005.
In addition, the FA registered it retroactively from 1 October 200415 for the purposes of sales tax, in order to be able to monitor the filing of the sales tax declaration for 2004.
In this VAT return, the taxable person declared intra-Community acquisitions from the Czech Republic worth 160 Euro (about 5,000 CZK).
3. In its VAT declaration for September 2004 as well as in its ZM for the third quarter of 2004, a Czech taxable person reported goods deliveries worth CZK 114,615 to a German taxpayer.
When reviewing the registration of the German taxpayer in the VIES system, the Czech tax official stated that this registration was only valid from 11 November 2004 and thus after the delivery of goods to Germany.
The Czech tax payer issued a supplementary VAT declaration stating sales from domestic deliveries worth CZK 114,615 and sales tax of CZK 21,777, which he paid.
Through a request to the local FA in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that the Czech taxpayer subsequently submitted a request for the resumption of the tax procedure in respect of the supplementary VAT return. As evidence, he submitted a confirmation from the German tax administration that the German taxpayer had been registered since January 1, 2000.
Accordingly, the Czech tax official reviewed the validity of the registration of the German taxpayer in the context of the international exchange of information.
According to the German information, the German taxpayer was not allocated a VAT ID number until 11 November 2004, i.e. after the date of delivery of the goods.
As a result, the Czech tax official dismissed the request to resume the tax procedure.
The BRH found that there had been no intra-Community acquisition of goods in this case because the German taxpayer had only received a VAT ID number on 11 November 2004.
The German recipient, however, declared both the acquisition as an intra-Community acquisition and the value-added tax, and also demanded the reimbursement of pre-taxes at the same rate.
Because this did not lead to a change in the amount of the tax liability of the German taxpayer, the German tax official did not correct the information in the VAT declaration.
The BRH also found that the company of the German taxpayer named in the request for information was changed during the processing of the reply in Germany, which led to confusion between two German taxpayers.
This change in the name of the German taxpayer also confused the Czech tax official.
4.
As part of the international exchange of information, the German tax official reviewed the purchase of goods in the first quarter of 2005 by a Czech taxpayer from a German taxpayer worth Euro22,686.
Through a request to the local tax official in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax official had examined in the course of an external examination with the Czech taxpayer whether the intra-EU supply had actually taken place and whether the Czech taxpayer had recorded and paid the invoice for the delivery of the goods.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the intra-EU purchase in his VAT return because the German supplier did not indicate his VAT ID number in the invoice, but only his tax number for transactions within Germany.
According to the VIES data, the German taxpayer is not registered for VAT in connection with intra-Community transactions until 21 April 2005, i.e. after delivery to the Czech taxpayer.
The Czech tax official also requested that the German tax administration send a copy of the registration certificate of the German tax payer, so that he could initiate a corresponding tax procedure if necessary.
The Czech FA considered this business to be the purchase of goods from a non-business (private) person in Germany and therefore did not set a sales tax for the purchase of goods from Germany.
The BRH found that under German law, a taxable person who supplies goods to other Member States does not have to have a VAT ID number for intra-Community supplies in order to benefit from the VAT exemption for such a delivery.
The supplier must only have the UStIdNr. Of the buyer in the other Member State and be able to prove the transport of the goods in question to the other Member State.
In this case, the turnover under German tax law is a (tax-exempt) intra-Community supply, which should be subject to employment taxation in the Czech Republic.
In any case, it is important that the Czech finance officer took note of this business incident, because the delivery of a machine of this value was not part of the core business of the German supplier.
As described in Section 4.6.2, the German CLO rejects requests for information on intra-Community transactions if they are below the minimum threshold of Euro15,000:5.
According to the VIES data, in the third quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth Euro12,561 from a German taxpayer.
The Czech tax official carried out an audit for this tax period.
In the framework of the intergovernmental assistance, the Czech financial administration requested the examination of this delivery of goods by means of a SCAC form.
The Czech taxpayer said that he had not received the goods, had never been in business with the German company and that the purchase of the goods in question had not been recorded with him.
The German financial administration rejected the request for the transfer of documents - contracts, orders, invoices and transport documents - because the turnover was less than Euro15,000 and no other justification had been given.
Since the Czech tax official did not receive documentation for the ex-post taxation of the purchased goods, the tax assessment was inconclusive, and the original tax assessment was maintained.
Following a request from the NKÚ, the BRH found that the German taxpayer acted as a "fiscal representative 17" (§ 22 (a) - (e) UStG).
The German taxpayer declared these deliveries in his VAT declaration and in the ZM.
His right to tax exemption has been recognised.
On the basis of the notification by the BRH, the German FA will send the documents required for the ex-post taxation of the purchased goods to the Czech Republic.
