12.
In the context of the international exchange of information, the German financial management asked for a review of the delivery of goods and the provision of services in the third quarter of 2005 by means of a SCAC form.
According to the request for information, during the period in question, the Czech taxpayer had supplied goods to the German taxpayer with a total value of Euro396.126 and provided services worth Euro11,885.
The NKÚ found that the Czech tax administration had carried out an audit on the Czech taxpayer in order to investigate this delivery.
In response to the request for information, the Czech tax administration announced that the Czech taxpayer had supplied and installed a production plant for the German one.
The Czech taxpayer supplied the individual parts of the production plant prior to the Czech Republic's accession to the EC and the production plant was assembled on the basis of the order after 1 May 2004.
The German taxpayer did not take down the assembled production plant and claimed faults.
In the third quarter of 2005, the Czech taxpayer charged the German production plant for Euro107,100 and Euro11,885 for services.
The German taxpayer received the bills, but did not recognise them and did not pay them.
By asking the local tax official in the Czech Republic, NKÚ found that all invoices on the books of the Czech taxpayer had been properly accounted for.
The VAT returns for the third quarter of 2005 included only the amounts documented by the Czech taxpayer relating to invoices invoiced after the first of May 2004.
The BRH found that, on the basis of the Czech financial management's reply, the local FA concluded that these transactions were a single (goods) delivery of the Czech taxpayer to the German assembly, including the assembly performed.
In this particular case, the place of performance of this so-called factory delivery is the place where the production plant is assembled.
The German recipient of the delivery of the work owes the sales tax in accordance with the German sales tax law.
At the same time, the recipient can claim a deduction in the same amount.
As the German taxpayer's liability for turnover remained unchanged, the German FA did not issue a correction to the VAT declaration.
13. According to the VIES data, in February 2005, Czech taxpayer A purchased a machine worth Euro58,000 from the German taxpayer C.
The Czech tax official sent a request for verification of this information to Germany.
In response to the request for information, the German side announced that the German taxpayer C had delivered this machine to the Czech taxpayer B in 2004, but returned it to the German taxpayer C in October 2004.
According to the German tax administration, the machine was not transported back to Germany, but to the establishment of the German taxpayer C in the Czech Republic.
The reply to the request for information also revealed that the German taxpayer C had delivered the machine to the Czech taxpayer A in February 2005.
He received the machine at the headquarters of the German taxpayer's office in the Czech Republic.
Since this delivery (from C to A) took place only within the Czech Republic, there was no intra-Community delivery of goods.
By asking the local tax official responsible for the taxable person, the NKÚ found that, according to the VIES data, in the third quarter of 2004, the German taxpayer C had supplied the Czech taxpayer with goods (another machine) worth Euro88.027.
Tax payer B said he did not receive the goods, so the local Czech tax official sent a request for information to Germany.
The answer was that the machine had been delivered.
In the course of further investigations with the taxable person B, the tax official stated that the machine, worth Euro88.027, had not been registered with the taxable person B and that it could be the same type of machine as the branch of the German taxpayer C had delivered to the Czech taxpayer A in February 2005.
The NKÚ also found that the local Czech tax official responsible for the taxable person A had carried out an audit on the latter.
The tax official had the invoice of the German taxable person C of 7 February 2005, in which the taxable person A is indicated as the recipient of the machine.
The Czech tax official noted that taxable person A had not recorded this invoice.
Taxable A had signed a lease agreement with another Czech company, the subject of which was a machine of the same type.
The leasing company delivered the machine on February 9, 2005 and also provided transport.
The Czech FA did not use the information provided in the reply to the request for information to determine the tax liability of the taxpayer A.
The BRH found that the German taxpayer C had delivered the machine, worth Euro88.027, not to the Czech Republic, but to another German taxpayer D.
Accordingly, there was no intra-Community supply of goods, but a taxable supply within Germany.
Consequently, the German tax official did not recognise the claim of the German taxpayer C for VAT exemption and corrected the information in his tax return.
The German taxpayer D supplied the machine to the Czech taxpayer B.
According to German law, this delivery was not subject to tax in Germany, but was subject to VAT in the Czech Republic.
The BRH also found that the German taxpayer C had indicated in its ZM for the first quarter of 2005 the delivery of a machine worth Euro58,000 to the Czech taxpayer A.
This delivery was not checked during the tax audit carried out by the German FA.
