The Czech taxpayer was not registered as a taxable person in Germany and had not taxed the sale of the goods in question in either the Czech Republic or Germany.
All of these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany, and the Czech tax official provided this information in his response to the request for information to the German tax administration.
Through a request to the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ found that the Czech taxpayer had issued a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004 on the basis of a tax assessment, in which he declared, among other things, the value of the goods he had purchased from a German taxpayer and at the same time asserted the right of deduction for the purchase from other Member States.
In his Czech VAT declaration, he did not declare a sales tax on the sale of goods in Germany.
On the basis of a supplementary VAT declaration issued after the external audit, the Czech tax official fixed the VAT liability unchanged.
According to Czech legislation, in this case, there was no purchase of goods from other Member States, as the goods were not shipped or transported from another Member State to the Czech Republic.
Thus, the Czech tax official came to the wrong conclusion during the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which revealed that the goods had not left Germany, the German tax official corrected the tax return of the German taxpayer and demanded the payment of sales tax worth Euro1,600.
In addition, the competent FA sent a control notice to the FA, which is responsible for the actual recipient of the goods, to ensure that the resale of those goods is properly taxed.
In the following cases, traders declared intra-Community supplies that may not have been carried out:
18.
The Czech tax official received a request for information from the German tax administration on whether the Czech taxpayer had purchased a car worth Euro47,400 from the German taxpayer in February 2005.
A copy of the VAT registration certificate of the Czech taxpayer was attached to the request for information.
As a further attachment, a photocopy of the passport was attached to the person who was supposed to have transferred the vehicle.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech tax official found that the passport had been stolen, that the person named in it had not imported a vehicle into the Czech Republic and said that he had no contacts with a German taxpayer.
The VAT registration certificate, the imprint of which had been sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech tax administration.
With this information, the Czech tax official answered the request for information and at the same time stated that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
By asking the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ stated that the Czech taxpayer does not have his seat at the address indicated in the commercial register and that the company's managing director cannot be reached.
Following a tax redress procedure for the tax period of February 2005, the Czech tax official set the tax liability of the Czech taxpayer at zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech finance officer found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had purchased it on the basis of an internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local German tax official had rejected the German taxpayer's claim to exempt this supply from VAT on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of Euro3,000 between the value of the purchased goods specified in the VAT declaration and the reported values from other Member States.
A Czech taxpayer should have delivered goods worth Euro89,424 to a German taxpayer in the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005.
Since the acquisition declared by the German taxpayer did not comply with the VIES data, the German tax official asked for the verification of deliveries and their payment as part of the intergovernmental exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech tax official stated that the sole managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was presumed to be a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech tax payer issued a VAT declaration and a ZM, which was signed by a person not authorised to do so, namely this shareholder of the company, after the deletion of the managing director in the commercial register.
The accountant of the Czech taxpayer informed the tax official that the owner of the capital had paid the payment received for the goods invoiced in euros into the company's account.
Cash receipts have not been issued.
Through a request to the local Czech FA, the NKÚ found that the tax official recognised the Czech taxpayer's right to VAT exemption for supplies of goods to other Member States worth CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German tax official did not correct the VAT declaration of the German buyer, since in the meantime a German court had confirmed the insolvency of the German taxpayer.
Since the previous external audit showed no signs of tax fraud, there was no prospect of actually being able to collect a fixed value-added tax debt.
20. According to the VIES data, in 2005, a German taxpayer purchased goods from the Czech Republic worth Euro4,251,196, according to which he had purchased goods worth Euro43,274 in the previous year.
The German taxpayer did not declare the intra-Community acquisitions either in his 2004 sales tax declaration or in the one for 2005.
In addition, it did not declare any initial sales in terms of value.
Due to these disagreements, the German FA submitted a request for information concerning the 4th quarter of 2005 and the 1st quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community supplies of goods for a total value of CZK 167,246,083.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side asked to check whether the delivery reported by the Czech taxpayer had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech financial management stated that the German request could not be met because the Czech company did not have a managing director (or other legal representatives).
From the documents provided to NKÚ by the competent tax official, it can be seen that, together with the managing director of the Czech taxpayer, a protocol was drawn up on 30 March 2006 on the start of the audit of turnover for the 4th quarter of 2004 and the period from January to December 2005.
At the same time, the tax payer was asked by the tax official to provide all accounting and tax documents for that period, but failed to do so.
According to the commercial register, the term of office of the sole managing director expired on 16 May 2005 without the appointment of a new managing director.
The Czech taxpayer has not issued any turnover tax returns since April 2006.
In the context of the parallel examination, the NKÚ, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community supplies between the Czech Republic and Germany, which were not the subject of a prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two courts of auditors exchanged information on the cases examined through the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the competent FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to do taxable business in Germany.
On the basis of this information, the company was registered as of June 2005, but did not receive a German VAT ID number.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the production of wind turbines and their delivery to Austria on behalf of, at the risk and for the account of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient production capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the order to a German taxpayer (UDE) resident in Germany.
The following figure shows the contractual relations and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account.
Due to the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
- Because the freight forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out in its own name, at its own risk and for its own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the receiver is registered as taxable in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE), since the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is different from the State of the Czech company19.
Accordingly, the delivery is properly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- The delivery of wind turbines produced in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- The delivery of the remaining wind turbines, which were manufactured in Germany, took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided both intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community supplies from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community supplies either in its German tax returns or in its ZM delivered to the German CLO.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community supplies uniformly as intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic.
The NKÚ found that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, cooperation would be required from at least four financial administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German), although in this case there is no evidence of tax fraud or evasion.
In addition, the NKÚ and the BRH examined case designs to show the size of the differences between the information in the VAT returns and the VIES data caused by the different legislation in 2004.
The cases examined also show that it will take some time for taxpayers and the tax authorities to apply the new legislation:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer reported goods deliveries to a German taxpayer with a total value of CZK 792,977,452.
During the same period, another Czech taxpayer reported intra-Community supplies to another German taxpayer in his ZM for a total value of CZK 18,157,265.
The information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ revealed that both were electricity supplies.
Both Czech taxable persons took into account the above supplies in their domestic accounts in accordance with Czech Law No. 235/2004, applicable in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of the NKÚ found that in 2004 different legal regulations concerning the supply and purchase of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany applied.
Whereas in the Czech Republic, taxable persons declared the supply of electrical energy as an intra-Community supply of goods in accordance with the provisions of Law No. 235/2004 in force in 2004, according to the German legislation in force in 2004, it was not an intra-Community acquisition of goods, but taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in legal regulations were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law No. 635/2004, which changed some tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. During the examination of intra-Community supplies or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech taxable person declared intra-Community supplies for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 to a German taxpayer with a total value of CZK 240,411,163 and another Czech taxpayer declared intra-Community supplies for the same period to another German taxpayer with a value of CZK 263.470.776.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ revealed that in both cases it had been the supply of electrical energy.
In accordance with the provisions of Law No 235/2004, applicable from 1 January 2005, the place of performance for the supply of electrical energy shall be the place where the purchaser has his legal domicile, his place of business or his place of business for which the delivery is made.
For this reason, the Czech taxpayers should not have indicated the electricity supplies in their ZM for 2005.
The fact that both taxable persons treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies led to a difference in the amount of CZK 503,881.939 in VIES.
Concluding remarks
Through cooperation, the objectives of the BRH and the NKÚ have been achieved.
Both courts of auditors gained in-depth knowledge of the systems of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legislation governing VAT administration.
During the parallel examinations, there were interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or purchases.
Some of them are worth watching.
On the basis of the audit results, both courts of auditors drew up recommendations on the management of sales tax.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a control review should be part of the follow-up.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of the two courts of auditors is the basis for the successful implementation of future audits in the area of VAT administration.
